{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"59b7c172-4451-44b3-808a-e4f8f8a56ac1","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the easiest way to capture a CPU profile for .NET apps.\n\n### Setup\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect for 30 seconds (adjust as needed)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30 -o trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Analyze\n- Open `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n- Or convert to Speedscope format for browser-based viewing:\n  ```powershell\n  dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n  ```\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper OS-level detail)\nIf you need kernel-level CPU stacks (driver issues, GC, JIT):\n```powershell\n# Download PerfView.exe from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with `dotnet-trace` — it's lightweight, doesn't require a reboot, and gives managed call stacks. Escalate to PerfView if you need unmanaged/kernel stacks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"87e3bfd0-f090-4b54-9fe7-83c75a64e492","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":373},"id":"fd0df625-58a7-4c74-aac7-1487792066fa","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:51:15.884Z","parentId":"51930ac9-6c7b-411d-bcad-6ac4102b94c6"}
